Absolutely flabbergasted that these seven pieces were accepted in the Society of Illustrators 65th Annual Exhibitions. 
My sincerest gratitude to the jury and everything that @soi128 stands for. SUPER THANK YOUS to each and every client for their continued trust and confidence in the wonky worlds that I create. Credits to @jonwoidka @katiejaneklim @tjklunebooks @torbooks @irenegallo @tordotcompub @lavietidhar @maevenn @sophieandersonauthor @scholasticinc @neillangdesign @magnetreps

Whisper the word ‘Rosebud’ 
It was a challenge to re-create arguably the most iconic movie prop of all time, the childhood sled of Citizen Cane. Art Director @goecke had the brilliant idea to also fold in the snow globe which was part of that iconic revealing scene. And then add yet another layer by having William Hearst III the publisher of @altajournal and (the grandson of William Hearst of whom Citizen Cane was loosely based upon) holding the Rosebud Award. 
Congratulations to all those nominated and awarded a Rosebud Award. 

May we all not loose sight of what truly is the core of what makes life worth living.
The wolves were released today and I am elated. Thank you to @neillangdesign @torbooks and especially@tjklunebooks for the trust and confidence in the artwork I make.
Indiana had a break in the weather today, it was good to blow some cobwebs off.
I sure can’t do hat tricks, but here is a sneak peek of my new short “Hat Trick” for @mtaartsdesign Now playing at Grand Central Madison terminal in NYC.

I am happy to announce “Hat Trick” my two-minute stop-motion animation for @mtaartsdesign that celebrates the opening of Grand Central Madison, is now showing on the five-channel LED screens at the north end of the concourse. “Hat Trick” depicts a playful cat-and-mouse chase through Grand Central Madison between a man and his bowler hat, inspired by the magical feeling of traveling throughout New York on the MTA’s vast system. Portals appear and whisk the characters from one place to another with motion, timing, and surprise, doubling as a metaphor for the experience of moving through everyday life. 

If you’d like to read a bit about process behind “Hat Trick” that can be found on my blog —> link in bio.

‘Descension’ 12x28x13 inches. mixed media: plywood, cardboard, paper, fabric, polymer clay, wire, lightbulb, with carved Redbud and Basswood. 
I could hardly believe that Mike Mignola would consider asking me to create a piece based on his visuals for Pinocchio. I read Carlo Collodi’s original version and did my best to avoid all current iterations of the story to aim to keep it honest to Mike Mignola’s vision. The story is a tough journey that cuts close to my heart, having experienced the loss of a child paired with my own self-doubts about the work I create. All things that build a life experience that I wouldn’t dare wish to change. Thank you @artofmm I am truly honored. 

On display 3/22 to 7/8 at The Society of Illustrators NYC @soi128
Descension

Northern Lights: I haven’t experienced the aurora borealis in person. During our winter months, I often turn to reading books on the history of polar exploration. Most recently ‘Alone on the Ice’ about the Australian Douglas Mawson. ‘In the Land of White Death’ about Russian Valerian Albanov. ‘The Last Viking’ about Norwegian Roald Amundsen. The piece isn’t directly about these explorers, but more of contemplation on what draws us to these places. Using the precarious Taubanesentralen in Svalbard, Norway as the backdrop and the elusive BMW Gleitkettenkraftrad as the preferred mode of transportation.
A fly-through of the ‘Northern Lights’ set. Plus a little behind the scenes on how the light effect was created.

Mixed Media: polymer clay, wood wire, copper, foam, fabric, plastic and paper. 
The chair cover is from the lining of an antique clarinet box. 
The feline does have a few small cracks. this is likely due to uneven curing of the polymer clay, a common problem especially when working under editorial deadlines. It has a full wire armature so the cracks will not result in breakage, just surface flaws. The piece is priced with these flaws in mind.

‘BoneShaker’ 13.5 x 18x 9 inches. Mixed Media: wood, polymer clay, copper, brass, gears, rolling bearings, cardboard and plastic.
I had the opportunity to travel to Paris earlier this year, it was there that I stumbled across an early velocipede by Pierre Michaux circa 1865 at the @museeartsetmetiersparis the artifact is titled: ‘Michaux Velocipe with a wavy body’ 

BoneShaker combines my fascination with two wheeled propulsion along with a curiosity with automata, bringing about my first attempt at animating a character in the present instead of through a lens. What I enjoy about automata is that it requires the viewer to be present and directly engaged. 

Available if interested—> link in bio

Last week Microsoft announced an upcoming feature in it’s PAINT software that would allow users to remove an entire background with a single click. The image they demonstrated this new feature with was “Flight” artwork that I created as a screensaver for the release of Windows 7 nearly 15 years ago. They had all the rights to use the image for this demo and the the original contract even stated that they didn't have to credit the image to me. (but that would have been a kind gesture) 
At the time of the project, when the contract was signed (before the image was even concepted) I had no idea how long-lasting this image would become. Thanks to everyone that noticed the image was mine.🙏

I heard that Climate Week is taking place right now Sept 17-24 in NYC. I reckon it’s gonna be lots of talk and little action. Here’s a short I optimistically created back in 2014 thinking we could make a difference. Honestly, I’m still optimistic, but mostly on a local level.

‘Frayed’ A reflection on emotions that layer up and can’t be described by words. 
I recall being told once, to be like a duck, calm on the surface but working like crazy under the surface. I understand the metaphor here, but I also know that not being able to show your true emotion can build up after time and be hard to bear.

‘Frayed'

Delighted to announce that ‘Descension’ was accepted into the upcoming 66th Annual Exhibit at the Museum of Illustration at the @soi128 in New York City. The exhibit will run Jan 31- Mar 16th 2024. My gratitude to the international jury of illustrators, art directors and designers. Thank you to @artofmm for bringing me in on this project. Last but not least, to the younger me who never got in the exhibit back in the day, here’s to sticking with it!
My strongest argument in the case that big bikes are overrated. 1965 Harley Davidson Pacer 175cc 2-stroke

Sometimes pursuing personal work can be daunting especially when, as a commercial illustrator, you’re not getting paid. However, I feel it’s important to pursue this work to not only help sharpen skills and ideas, but to also allow your work to grow and evolve. The hard part for me is just giving myself permission to actually do it. I’m tickled down to my frozen fingertips that ’Northern Lights’ was accepted into the upcoming 66th Annual Exhibit at the Museum of Illustration @soi128 located in New York City. The exhibit will run Jan 31- Mar 16th 2024. My gratitude to the international jury of illustrators, art directors and designers. If you’re interested there’s a limited edition print of this, link in bio.
For the curious out there. This shot took over 185 takes to get the ‘right’ light effect. The green streaking is me moving a light in the background during a long exposure.
